Definition 2.1. If $P$ is a $C$-coloured operad, a subset $J\subseteq C$ is called an ideal relative to $P$ if $P(c_{1},\ldots,c_{n};c)=0$ whenever $n\geq 1$, $c\in J$, and $c_{i}\not\in J$ for some $i\in\{1,\ldots,n\}$.
Definition 3.3. We say that a localization $(L,\eta)$ on a closed symmetric monoidal category $\mathcal{E}$ is closed if, for every $L$-equivalence $f\colon X\longrightarrow Y$ and every $L$-local object $Z$, the map $\mathop{\textrm{\rm Hom}}\nolimits_{\mathcal{E}}(f,Z)\colon\mathop{\textrm{\rm Hom% }}\nolimits_{\mathcal{E}}(Y,Z)\longrightarrow\mathop{\textrm{\rm Hom}}% \nolimits_{\mathcal{E}}(X,Z)$ is an isomorphism in $\mathcal{E}$.
Définition 4.3 : Soit $A$ une categorie d’ordre $n$ avec objets $x_{1},\ldots,x_{n}$, on dit que $x_{i}$ et $x_{j}$ sont isomorphes s’il existe $f\in A(x_{i},x_{j})$ et $g\in A(x_{j},x_{i})$ tels que $fg=1_{x_{j}}$ et $gf=1_{x_{i}}$.
Définition 4.4 : Soit $A$ une catégorie telle qu’il existe deux objets distincts $x_{i}$ et $x_{j}$ ($i\neq j$) qui sont isomorphes, on dira que $A$ est non-réduite. On dira que $A$ est réduite sinon,c’est-à-dire si deux objets distincts sont toujours non-isomorphes. On dira qu’une matrice $M$ est non-réduite s’il existe $i\neq j$ tel que $\forall k,\;\;M_{ki}=M_{kj}$ et $\forall k,\;\;M_{ik}=M_{jk},$ cela veut dire que la ligne $i$ égale la ligne $j$ et la colonne $i$ égale la colonne $j$. On dira qu’une matrice $M$ est réduite si elle n’est pas non-réduite.
Definition 3.1 (Left) action of a double category $d,r:D_{1}\rightarrow D_{0}$ on a category $p:M\rightarrow D_{0}$ over $D_{0}$ is a functor $\varphi$ such that (1)The diagram is commutative $\begin{array}[]{ccc}D_{1}\times_{D_{0}}M&\buildrel\varphi\over{\rightarrow}&M% \\ &&\\ \quad\quad r\circ\pi_{1}&\searrow&\quad\downarrow\;p\\ &&\\ &&D_{0}\end{array}$ where the bundle product $D_{1}\times_{D_{0}}M$ is defined by the diagram $\begin{array}[]{ccc}D_{1}\times_{D_{0}}M&\buildrel\pi_{2}\over{\rightarrow}&M% \\ \pi_{1}\downarrow&&\quad\downarrow\;p\\ D_{1}&\buildrel r\over{\rightarrow}&D_{0}\end{array}$ (2)The diagram is commutative with precise to an isomorphism $\begin{array}[]{ccccc}(D_{1}\times_{D_{0}}D_{1})\times_{D_{0}}M&\buildrel\cong% \over{\rightarrow}&D_{1}\times_{D_{0}}(D_{1}\times_{D_{0}}M)&\buildrel id_{D_{% 1}}\times_{D_{0}}\varphi\over{\longrightarrow}&D_{1}\times_{D_{0}}M\\ \otimes\times_{D_{0}}id_{M}\downarrow&&&&\ \ \downarrow\varphi\\ D_{1}\times_{D_{0}}M&&\buildrel\varphi\over{\longrightarrow}&&M\end{array}$ and there exists a functor isomorphism $\varphi$ such that $\forall\;\xi,\xi^{\prime}\in Obj(D_{1}),\;m\in Obj(M_{1})\;\quad\varphi_{\xi,% \xi^{\prime},m}:(\xi*\xi^{\prime})*m\rightarrow\xi*(\xi^{\prime}*m)$ (3) For the unit functor we have a functor isomorphism $\chi:\varphi\circ(ID\times id_{M})\widetilde{\longrightarrow}id_{M}$ or for objects $\forall\;A\in Obj(D_{0}),\;m\in Obj(M_{1})\quad\chi_{A,m}:ID_{A}*m\widetilde{% \longrightarrow}m$
Definition 1.1 A double category $D$ consists of the following: (1) A category $D_{0}$ of objects $Obj(D_{0})$ and morphisms $Mor(D_{0})$ of $0$-level. (2) A category $D_{1}$ of objects $Obj(D_{1})$ of $1$-level and morphisms $Mor(D_{1})$ of $2$-level. (3) Two functors $d,r:D_{1}\overrightarrow{\to}D_{0}.$ (4) A composition functor $\ast:D_{1}\times_{D_{0}}D_{1}\to D_{1}$ where the bundle product is defined by commutative diagram $\begin{array}[]{ccc}D_{1}\times_{D_{0}}D_{1}&\mathop{\rightarrow}\limits^{\pi_% {2}}&D_{1}\\ \pi_{1}\downarrow&&\quad\downarrow d\\ D_{1}&\mathop{\rightarrow}\limits^{r}&D_{0}\end{array}$ (5) A unit functor $ID:D_{0}\to D_{1}$, which is a section of $d,r$. The above data is subject to Associativity Axiom and Unit Axiom. If both of them are fulfilled only up to equivalence then the double category is called a weak double category, if they are fulfilled strictly then it is a strong double category.
Definition 2.1. Let ${\mathcal{A}}$ be a DG category. A DG module $M\in{\mathcal{A}}\text{-mod}$ is called h-projective (resp. h-injective) if for any acyclic DG module $N\in{\mathcal{A}}\text{-mod}$ the complex $\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{A}}}(M,N)$ (resp. $\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{A}}}(N,M)$) is acyclic. We denote by $\text{h-proj}({\mathcal{A}})\subset{\mathcal{A}}\text{-mod}$ (resp. $\text{h-inj}({\mathcal{A}})\subset{\mathcal{A}}\text{-mod}$) the full DG subcategory which consists of h-projective (resp. h-injective) DG modules. We also call $M\in{\mathcal{A}}\text{-mod}$ h-flat if for any acyclic $N\in{\mathcal{A}}^{op}\text{-mod}$ the complex $M\otimes_{{\mathcal{A}}}N$ of $k$-modules is also acyclic.
Definition 3.3. For any small DG category ${\mathcal{A}}\in\operatorname{dgcat}_{k},$ and any full thick essentially small subcategory ${\mathcal{T}}\subset D({\mathcal{A}}),$ we call the DG category $\widehat{{\mathcal{A}}}_{{\mathcal{T}}}$ ”derived double centralizer of ${\mathcal{T}}$”.
Definition 3.7. Let ${\mathcal{D}}$ be an essentially small Karoubian complete enhanced triangulated category, and ${\mathcal{T}}\subset{\mathcal{D}}$ be a full thick triangulated subcategory. Define the formal completion $\widehat{{\mathcal{D}}}_{{\mathcal{T}}}$ of ${\mathcal{D}}$ along ${\mathcal{T}},$ together with a restriction functor $\kappa^{*}:{\mathcal{D}}\to\widehat{{\mathcal{D}}}_{{\mathcal{T}}},$ as follows. Choosing a set of generators in ${\mathcal{D}},$ we may replace ${\mathcal{D}}$ by $\operatorname{Perf}({\mathcal{A}})$ for some small DG category ${\mathcal{A}}.$ Then put $\widehat{{\mathcal{D}}}_{{\mathcal{T}}}:=\operatorname{Perf}(\widehat{{% \mathcal{A}}}_{{\mathcal{T}}}),\quad\kappa^{*}:={\mathbf{L}}\iota_{{\mathcal{T% }}}^{*}:{\mathcal{D}}=\operatorname{Perf}({\mathcal{A}})\to\operatorname{Perf}% (\widehat{{\mathcal{A}}}_{{\mathcal{T}}})=\widehat{{\mathcal{D}}}_{{\mathcal{T% }}}.$
Definition 2.6. Let ${\mathcal{A}}\in\operatorname{dgcat}_{k}$ be a DG category. We say that ${\mathcal{A}}$ is proper (over $k$) if for any two objects $X,Y\in Ob({\mathcal{A}}),$ the complex $\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{A}}}(X,Y)$ is a perfect $k$-module.
Definition 3.5. Let ${\mathcal{D}}$ be an enhanced triangulated category with infinite direct sums, which is compactly generated by a set of objects. Let ${\mathcal{T}}\subset{\mathcal{D}}$ be an essentially small full thick triangulated subcategory. We define the formal completion $\widehat{{\mathcal{D}}}_{{\mathcal{T}}}$ of ${\mathcal{D}}$ along ${\mathcal{T}},$ together with a restriction functor $\kappa^{*}:{\mathcal{D}}\to\widehat{{\mathcal{D}}}_{{\mathcal{T}}},$ as follows. Choosing a set of compact generators in ${\mathcal{D}},$ we may replace ${\mathcal{D}}$ by $D({\mathcal{A}})$ for some small DG category ${\mathcal{A}}.$ Then put $\widehat{{\mathcal{D}}}_{{\mathcal{T}}}:=D(\widehat{{\mathcal{A}}}_{{\mathcal{% T}}}),\quad\kappa^{*}:={\mathbf{L}}\iota_{{\mathcal{T}}}^{*}:{\mathcal{D}}=D({% \mathcal{A}})\to D(\widehat{{\mathcal{A}}}_{{\mathcal{T}}})=\widehat{{\mathcal% {D}}}_{{\mathcal{T}}}.$
Definition 2.2. Let ${\mathcal{A}}\in\operatorname{dgcat}_{k}$ be an h-flat DG category. We say that ${\mathcal{A}}$ is smooth (over $k$) if ${\mathcal{I}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}\in\operatorname{Perf}({\mathcal{A}}^{op}\otimes{% \mathcal{A}}),$ where ${\mathcal{I}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}\in D({\mathcal{A}}^{op}\otimes{\mathcal{A}}),% \quad{\mathcal{I}}_{{\mathcal{A}}}(X,Y)=\operatorname{Hom}_{{\mathcal{A}}}(Y,X).$ An arbitrary DG category ${\mathcal{A}}\in\operatorname{dgcat}_{k}$ is said to be smooth if it is quasi-equivalent to smooth h-flat DG category.
Definition 5.1. For a morphism $s:x\to y$ in the category $I,$ we put $r(s):=y,$ $l(s)=x.$ We denote by $\overline{\operatorname{Mor}(I)}$ the set of non-identical morphisms in $I.$
Definition 3.2. Let $F:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{D}}$ be a dominant tensor functor between fusion categories. The Frobenius-Perron index of $F$ is the ratio $\operatorname{FPdim}{\mathcal{C}}/\operatorname{FPdim}{\mathcal{D}}$; we denote it by $\operatorname{FPind}(F)$ or $\operatorname{FPind}({\mathcal{C}}:{\mathcal{D}})$.
Definition 5.16. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a fusion category. A full fusion subcategory ${\mathcal{C}}^{\prime}$ of ${\mathcal{C}}$ is called normal if there exists a normal dominant functor of fusion categories $F:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{C}}^{\prime\prime}$ such that ${\mathcal{C}}^{\prime}\simeq\mathfrak{Ker}_{F}$.
Definition 4.20. A normal $\Bbbk$-linear right exact Hopf monad $T$ on a tensor category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is cocommutative if for any morphism $g:T(\textbf{1})\to\textbf{1}$ and any object $X$ of ${\mathcal{C}}$, the following square is commutative: $\xymatrix@C5em{T(X)\ar[r]^{T_{2}(X,\textbf{1})\quad}\ar[d]_{T_{2}(\textbf{1},X% )}&T(X)\otimes T(\textbf{1})\ar[d]^{\operatorname{id}_{T(X)}\otimes\,g}\\ T(\textbf{1})\otimes T(X)\ar[r]_{g\,\otimes\,\operatorname{id}_{T(X)}}&T(X).}$
Definition 2.2. A tensor functor $F:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{C}}^{\prime\prime}$ is dominant if it satisfies the equivalent conditions of Lemma 2.1.
Definition 4.17. An action of a group $G$ on a tensor category ${\mathcal{C}}$ (by tensor autoequivalences) is a strong monoidal functor $\rho:\underline{G}\to\underline{\operatorname{End}}_{\otimes}{\mathcal{C}}.$ In other words, it consists in the following data: (1) For each $g\in G$, a tensor endofunctor $\rho^{g}:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{C}}$; (2) For each pair $g,h\in G$, a monoidal isomorphism $\rho^{g,h}_{2}:\rho^{g}\rho^{h}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{\longrightarrow}% }\rho^{gh}$; (3) A monoidal isomorphism $\rho_{0}:\operatorname{id}_{\mathcal{C}}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\sim}}{{% \longrightarrow}}\rho^{1}$; such that for any $g,h,k$ in $G$ the following diagrams commute: $\xymatrix{\rho^{g}\rho^{h}\rho^{k}\ar[r]^{\rho^{g,h}_{2}\rho^{k}}\ar[d]_{\rho^% {g}\rho^{h,k}_{2}}&\rho^{gh}\ar[d]^{\rho^{gh,k}_{2}}\rho^{k}&&\rho^{g}\ar[r]^{% \rho^{g}\rho_{0}}\ar[d]_{\rho_{0}\rho^{g}}\ar[rd]^{=}&\rho^{g}\rho^{1}\ar[d]^{% \rho^{g,1}_{2}}\\ \rho^{g}\rho^{hk}\ar[r]_{\rho^{g,hk}_{2}}&\rho^{ghk}&&\rho^{1}\rho^{g}\ar[r]_{% \rho^{1,g}_{2}}&\rho^{g}.}$ Observe that if $G$ is a monoidal action of $G$ on ${\mathcal{C}}$, the $\rho^{g}$’s are in fact tensor autoequivalences of ${\mathcal{C}}$, $\rho^{g^{-1}}$ being quasi-inverse to $\rho^{g}$ for all $g\in G$.
Definition 5.18. A fusion category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is simple if ${\mathcal{C}}$ is not tensor equivalent to $\operatorname{vect}_{\Bbbk}$ and for every exact sequence of fusion categories ${\mathcal{C}}^{\prime}\to{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{C}}^{\prime\prime},$ either ${\mathcal{C}}^{\prime}$ or ${\mathcal{C}}^{\prime\prime}$ is tensor equivalent to $\operatorname{vect}_{\Bbbk}$.
Definition 4.27. A bimonad $T$ on a braided category ${\mathcal{C}}$ is braided if the following diagram is commutative: $\xymatrix@C5em{T(X\otimes Y)\ar[r]^{T_{2}(X,Y)}\ar[d]_{T(c_{X,Y})}&T(X)\otimes T% (Y)\ar[d]^{c_{T(X),T(Y)}}\\ T(Y\otimes X)\ar[r]^{T_{2}(Y,X)}&T(Y)\otimes T(X)}$ for any $X,Y$ objects of $T$, where $c$ denotes the braiding of ${\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition 2.7. Let ${\mathcal{C}}^{\prime},{\mathcal{C}},{\mathcal{C}}^{\prime\prime}$ be tensor categories over $\Bbbk$. A sequence of tensor functors $\xymatrix{{\mathcal{C}}^{\prime}\ar[r]^{f}&{\mathcal{C}}\ar[r]^{F}&{\mathcal{C% }}^{\prime\prime}}$ is an exact sequence of tensor categories if the following conditions hold: (1) The tensor functor $F$ is dominant and normal; (2) The tensor functor $f$ is a full embedding; (3) The essential image of $f$ is $\mathfrak{Ker}_{F}$; Two exact sequences of tensor categories $\xymatrix{{\mathcal{C}}^{\prime}\ar[r]^{f_{1}}&{\mathcal{C}}_{1}\ar[r]^{F_{1}}% &{\mathcal{C}}^{\prime\prime}}\quad\mbox{and}\quad\xymatrix{{\mathcal{C}}^{% \prime}\ar[r]^{f_{2}}&{\mathcal{C}}_{2}\ar[r]^{F_{2}}&{\mathcal{C}}^{\prime% \prime}}$ are equivalent if there exists a tensor equivalence $\lambda:{\mathcal{C}}_{1}\to{\mathcal{C}}_{2}$ such that $F_{1}\simeq F_{2}\lambda$ and $f_{2}\simeq\lambda f_{1}$ as tensor functors, that is, such that the diagram $\begin{CD}{\mathcal{C}}^{\prime}@>{f_{1}}>{}>{\mathcal{C}}_{1}@>{F_{1}}>{}>{% \mathcal{C}}^{\prime\prime}\\ @V{}V{=}V@V{}V{\lambda}V@V{}V{=}V\\ {\mathcal{C}}^{\prime}@>{f_{2}}>{}>{\mathcal{C}}_{2}@>{F_{2}}>{}>{\mathcal{C}}% ^{\prime\prime}.\end{CD}$ is commutative up to monoidal isomorphism. A exact sequence ${\mathcal{C}}^{\prime}\to{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{C}}^{\prime\prime}$ is called an extension of ${\mathcal{C}}^{\prime\prime}$ by ${\mathcal{C}}^{\prime}$; we also say that ${\mathcal{C}}$ is an extension of ${\mathcal{C}}^{\prime\prime}$ by ${\mathcal{C}}^{\prime}$.
Definition 5.13. Let $X$ be a trivial object of a tensor category ${\mathcal{C}}$. There is a unique half-braiding $\tau:X\otimes?\to?\otimes X$ such that $(X,\tau)$ is a trivial object in the center ${\mathcal{Z}}({\mathcal{C}})$ of ${\mathcal{C}}$. This half-braiding is called the trivial half-braiding for $X$.
Definition 4.19. A tensor functor $F:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{D}}$ between tensor categories is an equivariantization if there exists a finite group $G$ acting on ${\mathcal{D}}$ by tensor equivalences, and a tensor equivalence ${\mathcal{C}}\simeq{\mathcal{D}}^{G}$ over ${\mathcal{D}}$.
Definition 5.2. The commutative central algebra $(A,\sigma)$ associated with a tensor functor $F$ admitting a right adjoint is called the induced central algebra of $F$.
Definition 4.3. Let ${\mathcal{C}}$ be a tensor category. A $\Bbbk$-linear right exact Hopf monad $T$ on ${\mathcal{C}}$ is normal if $T(\textbf{1})$ is a trivial object of ${\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition 2.4. Let $F:{\mathcal{C}}\to{\mathcal{D}}$ be a tensor functor between tensor categories. Then $F$ is normal if for any object $X$ of ${\mathcal{C}}$, there exists a subobject $X_{0}\subset X$ such that $F(X_{0})$ is the largest trivial subobject of $F(X)$.
Definition 17. We call $A$ the motivic Donaldson-Thomas series of the pair $(R,W)$.
Definition 25. A function $f$ on smooth algebraic variety $X/{\mathbb{C}}$ is called topologically isotrivial at infinity if there exists a $C^{\infty}$-manifold with boundary $U\subset X({\mathbb{C}}),\,\,\dim_{\mathbb{R}}U=2\dim X$ such that $f_{|U}:U\to{\mathbb{C}}$ is proper, and a homeomorphism $h:\partial U\times[0,+\infty)\simeq X({\mathbb{C}})-\operatorname{int}U\,,\,\,% \,h(x,0)=x\mbox{ for }x\in\partial U\,,$ such that $f(h(x,t))=f(x)$ for any $x\in\partial U$.
Definition 9. For an object $N\in EMHS$ and a non-zero complex number $u$ we define Betti realization of $N$ at point $u$ to be the space of flat sections on the ray $[R,+\infty)\cdot u$ for sufficiently large $R\gg 0$ of the constructible sheaf $N_{Betti}^{MHM}[-1]$. Here $N_{Betti}^{MHM}$ is the object of $\operatorname{Perv}(\mathbb{A}^{1}({\mathbb{C}}),{\mathbb{Q}})$ underlying $N$, where $N$ is considered as an object of $MHM_{\mathbb{A}^{1}_{\mathbb{C}}}$. We denote this fiber by $N_{Betti,u}$.
Definition 21. Under the above assumptions the element $\Omega^{mot}(\gamma)$ is called motivic Donaldson-Thomas invariant of the pair $(R,W)$, stability function $Z$ and dimension vector $\gamma$.
Definition 3. A pre-cohomology theory ${\bf H}^{\bullet}$ is called cohomology theory if there exists a fiber functor $\mathcal{C}\to K^{\prime}-\operatorname{mod}$ for some field extension $K^{\prime}\supset K$ such that the resulting pre-cohomology theory is obtained by the extension of scalars from one of the standard theories.
Definition 13. A ${\mathbb{Z}}$-graded object $E^{\bullet}=\oplus_{n\in{\mathbb{Z}}}E^{n}$ of $EMHS$ is called pure if for any $n\in{\mathbb{Z}}$ component $E^{n}$ is pure of weight $n$.
Definition 5. The modified Cohomological Hall algebra $\mathcal{H}^{mod}$ is given by $\mathcal{H}^{mod}:=\oplus_{\gamma\in{\mathbb{Z}}^{I}_{\geqslant 0}}\,\mathcal{% H}^{mod}_{\gamma}\,,\,\,\,\,\,\mathcal{H}^{mod}_{\gamma}:=\mathcal{H}_{\gamma}% \otimes\left(\mathbb{T}^{\otimes 1/2}\right)^{\otimes\chi_{R}(\gamma,\gamma)}.$
Definition 15. For given $I$, a central charge $Z$ (a.k.a. stability function) is an additive map $Z:{\mathbb{Z}}^{I}\to{\mathbb{C}}$ such that the image of any of the standard base vectors lies in the upper-half plane $\mathbb{H}_{+}:=\{z\in{\mathbb{C}}\,|\,\operatorname{Im}(z)>0\}$. Central charge $Z$ is called generic if there are no two ${\mathbb{Q}}$-independent elements of ${{\mathbb{Z}}}_{\geqslant 0}^{I}$ which are mapped by $Z$ to the same straight line.
Definition 23. For given $I$ and $(G,t^{1/2})$, a non-singular $I$-colored factorization system is a factorization system together with a $\widetilde{G}\times\operatorname{Sym}_{\gamma_{1}}\times\operatorname{Sym}_{% \gamma_{2}}$-equivariant extension of $\mu_{\gamma_{1},\gamma_{2}}$ to a morphism of super coherent sheaves $\mathcal{F}_{\gamma_{1}}\boxtimes\mathcal{F}_{\gamma_{2}}\to\mathcal{F}_{% \gamma_{1}+\gamma_{2}}$ satisfying (in the notation of the previous definition) the constraints of commutativity and associativity on whole spaces $\mathbb{A}^{\gamma_{1}+\gamma_{2}}_{K}$ (resp. $\mathbb{A}^{\gamma_{1}+\gamma_{2}+\gamma_{3}}_{K}$) .
Definition 7. The category of exponential mixed Hodge structures $EMHS$ is the full subcategory of the category $MHM_{\mathbb{A}^{1}_{\mathbb{C}}}$ consisting of objects $M$ such that the corresponding perverse sheaf belongs to $\operatorname{Perv}_{0}(\mathbb{A}^{1}({\mathbb{C}}),{\mathbb{Q}})$. Equivalently, it is the image of endofunctor $\Pi$. It is a Tannakian category with the tensor product given by the additive convolution.
Definition 26. Tannakian category of monodromic mixed Hodge structures $MMHS$ is the full Tannakian subcategory of EMHS consisting of objects unramified on ${\mathbb{C}}^{*}\subset{\mathbb{C}}$.
Definition 11. The weight filtration of an exponential mixed Hodge structure is defined by the formula $W_{\leqslant n}^{\operatorname{EMHS}}M=W_{n}^{\operatorname{EMHS}}M:=p(W_{n}(i% (M)))\,,$ where in the RHS we consider the usual weight filtration for mixed Hodge modules.
Definition 19. For a $\lambda$-ring $B$ and a finite set $I$, a series $F\in B((q^{1/2}))[[(x_{i})_{i\in I}]]\,,$ where $q^{1/2},(x_{i})_{i\in I}$ are line elements (variables) is called admissible if it has a form $F=\operatorname{Sym}\left(\sum_{\gamma\in{\mathbb{Z}}_{\geqslant 0}^{I}-\{0\}}% \left(f_{\gamma}\cdot\sum_{n\geqslant 0}q^{n}\cdot\prod_{i\in I}x_{i}^{\gamma^% {i}}\right)\right),$ where $f_{\gamma}\in B[q^{\pm 1/2}]$ for any $\gamma=(\gamma^{i})_{i\in I}\in{\mathbb{Z}}_{\geqslant 0}^{I}-\{0\}$, and $\operatorname{Sym}(b):=\sum_{n\geqslant 0}\operatorname{Sym}^{n}(b)=\sum_{n% \geqslant 0}(-1)^{n}\lambda^{n}(-b)=\left(\sum_{n\geqslant 0}(-1)^{n}\lambda^{% n}(b)\right)^{-1}.$
Definition 1. The associative unital ${\mathbb{Z}}^{I}_{\geqslant 0}$-graded algebra $\mathcal{H}$ with the product $\mathsf{m}$ is called the Cohomological Hall algebra associated with the quiver $Q$.
Definition 16. A non-zero object $E$ is called semistable (for the central charge $Z$) if there is no non-zero subobject $F\subset E$ such that $\operatorname{Arg}(F)>\operatorname{Arg}(E)$.
Definition 24. A non-trivial representation of $R$ in coordinate spaces is called $T$-indecomposable if it can not be decomposed into the direct sum of two non-trivial subrepresentations in coordinate subspaces.
Definition 8. For an object $N\in EMHS$ and a non-zero complex number $u$ we define de Rham realization of $N$ at the point $u$ to be the fiber of ${\mathbb{C}}[y]$-module $FT(N_{DR}^{MHM})$ at the point $u^{-1}\in\operatorname{Spec}{\mathbb{C}}[y]$, where $N_{DR}^{MHM}$ is the algebraic holonomic ${\mathcal{D}}$-module underlying $N$, where $N$ is considered as an object of $MHM_{\mathbb{A}^{1}_{\mathbb{C}}}$. We denote this fiber by $N_{DR,u}$.
Definition 27. Let $X/{\mathbb{C}}$ be an algebraic variety endowed with a function $f\in\mathcal{O}(X)$, and a locally closed subset $X^{{\operatorname{sp}}}\subset X_{0}:=f^{-1}(0)$. The critical cohomology with compact support is defined as the cohomology of an object of $D^{b}(MMHS)\subset D^{b}(MHM_{\mathbb{A}^{1}_{\mathbb{C}}})$ , given by $(\mathbb{G}_{m}\to\mathbb{A}^{1}_{\mathbb{C}})_{!}\,(X^{\operatorname{sp}}% \times\mathbb{G}_{m}\to\mathbb{G}_{m})_{!}\,\left((X^{\operatorname{sp}}\times% \mathbb{G}_{m})\to(X_{0}\times\mathbb{G}_{m})\right)^{*}\,\phi_{\frac{f}{u}}{% \mathbb{Q}}_{X\times\mathbb{G}_{m}},$ where affine line $\mathbb{A}^{1}_{\mathbb{C}}$ is endowed with coordinate $u$. We will denote it by ${H}^{\bullet,crit}_{c,MMHS}(X^{{\operatorname{sp}}},f)$.
Definition 12. An object $M\in EMHS$ is called pure of weight $n\in{\mathbb{Z}}$ if $W^{EMHS}_{n}M=M$ and $W^{EMHS}_{n-1}M=0$.
Definition 20. We say that the quantum series $F$ is quantum admissible if for some (and hence by Theorem 9 any) choice of the ordered basis the corresponding classical series $F_{cl}$ is admissible.
Definition 4. An associative unital algebra $R$ over a field $\mathbf{k}$ is called smooth if it is finitely generated and formally smooth in the sense of D. Quillen and J. Cuntz, i.e. if the bimodule $\Omega^{1}_{R}:=\operatorname{Ker}(R\otimes_{\mathbf{k}}R\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle\operatorname{mult}}}{{\longrightarrow}}R)$ is projective. Here $\operatorname{mult}:R\otimes_{\mathbf{k}}R\to R$ is the product.
Definition 18. An element $x$ of a $\lambda$-ring is called line element if $x$ is invertible and $\lambda^{i}(x)=0\,,\,\,\,\,\forall i\geqslant 2\,.$
Definition 10. For an object $N\in EMHS$ we define complex vector space $N_{DR,0}$ to be the quotient $(d/dx)^{-j}F_{j}N_{DR}^{MHM}/(d/dx)^{-j}F_{j-1}N_{DR}^{MHM}$ for sufficiently large $j\gg 0$.
Definition 2. Let $\mathbf{k}$ be a field, and $K$ be another field, $\operatorname{char}(K)=0$. Assume that we are given a $K$-linear Tannakian category $\mathcal{C}$. A pre-cohomology theory over $\mathbf{k}$ with values in $\mathcal{C}$ is a contravariant tensor functor ${\bf H}^{\bullet}$ from the category of schemes of finite type over $\mathbf{k}$ to the tensor category ${\mathcal{C}}^{{\mathbb{Z}}-gr}$ of ${\mathbb{Z}}$-graded objects in $\mathcal{C}$ endowed with Koszul rule of signs.
